{"title_page": "Kathy Pham", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kathy Pham\n| image              = Kathy-pham.jpg\n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], [[Sup\u00e9lec]], [[MIT Media Lab]], [[Harvard University]]\n| employer           = [[United States Digital Service]], [[Google]], [[IBM]], Georgia Tech Research Institute\n| boards             = [[Anita Borg Institute for Women and Technology]], Make the Breast Pump Not Suck\n}}\n'''Kathy Pham''' is a Vietnamese American [[computer scientist]] and [[Product manager|product leader]]. She has held roles in leadership, engineering, product management, and data science at [[Google]], [[IBM]], the [[Georgia Tech Research Institute]], and Harris Healthcare<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/barack-obama-google-tech-talent-government-websites-118064|title=Obama's tech troops|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/01/21/uncle-sam-needs-more-geeks/|title=Uncle Sam Needs More Geeks \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/the-u-s-digital-service/why-i-joined-the-u-s-digital-service-24c6682afce2|title=Why I Joined the U.S. Digital Service|last=Service|first=The U. S. Digital|date=2015-01-28|website=The U.S. Digital Service|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> and served as a founding product and engineering member of the [[United States Digital Service]] (USDS) in the [[Executive Office of the President of the United States]] at [[White House|The White House]]. \n\nPham is a Fellow and Adjunct Lecturer at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]] where she created and teaches Product Management and Society, a Fellow at the [[Mozilla]], and Affiliate at the Harvard [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman Klein Center]] where she co-founded and leads the Ethical Tech Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2018/08/21/mozilla-announces-25-new-fellows-in-openness-science-and-tech-policy/|title=Mozilla Announces 26 New Fellows in Openness, Science, and Tech Policy \u2013 The Mozilla Blog|website=The Mozilla Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/digitalhks/meet-senior-fellow-kathy-pham-aa1f741bdfa1|title=Meet Senior Fellow Kathy Pham|last=Weber|first=Eva|date=2018-08-21|website=digital HKS|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/events/2018/luncheon/04/ethicaltech|title=Honoring All Expertise: Social Responsibility and Ethics in Tech|date=2018-07-06|website=Berkman Klein Center|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref> Pham co-leads the Responsible Computer Science Challenge at Mozilla, in partnership with [[Omidyar Network]], [[Craig Newmark]] Philanthropies, and Schmidt Futures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2018/10/10/announcing-a-competition-for-ethics-in-computer-science-with-up-to-3-5-million-in-prizes/|title=Announcing a Competition for Ethics in Computer Science, with up to $3.5 Million in Prizes \u2013 The Mozilla Blog|website=The Mozilla Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-03}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nPham\u2019s parents were [[Vietnamese boat people]], who spent several years in refugee camps before immigrating to the United States. Her brother, [[United States Marine Corps]] Captain David Pham, was presented the [[Purple Heart]] medal during combat operations in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.gatech.edu/hg/item/365761|title=Government & Community Relations {{!}} Georgia Institute of Technology {{!}} Atlanta, GA|website=www.gov.gatech.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://phimublog.com/2015/08/07/vibrant-voice-kathy-pham/|title=Vibrant Voice \u2013 Kathy Pham|date=2015-08-07|work=A Vibrant View|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPham attended [[Windsor Forest High School]] in [[Savannah, Georgia]] where she was a member of the volleyball team and graduated as [[Salutatorian]] of her graduating class.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wtoc.com/story/27896047/savannah-woman-selected-to-attend-the-state-of-the-union-address|title=Savannah woman selected to attend the State of the Union Address|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPham earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Computer science|Computer Science]] from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]. She also holds a [[Master of Science]] in Computer Science from both the Georgia Institute of Technology and [[Sup\u00e9lec|Supelec]], specializing in cryptography and human computer interaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gatech.edu/2015/01/20/georgia-tech-grad-among-white-house-guests-state-union|title=Georgia Tech grad among White House guests for State of the Union|website=www.news.gatech.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> While in university, Pham was the chair of Georgia Tech's Women in Computing,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cc.gatech.edu/compiler/archive/compiler-November08.html|title=Compiler - November 2008|website=www.cc.gatech.edu|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> director of technology at Phi Mu Fraternity, researcher in the Bio-Medical Informatics and Bio-Imaging Lab,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openwetware.org/wiki/Summer_2006_Workshop|title=Summer 2006 Workshop - OpenWetWare|website=openwetware.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> and founded the southeast chapter of [[Unite For Sight|United for Sight]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://coe.gatech.edu/news/entrepreneurial-upstarts|title=Entrepreneurial Upstarts|last=km78|date=2015-06-24|work=College of Engineering|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nPham began her career as a software engineer building flights simulation and healthcare interoperability software at the Georgia Tech Research Institute and Harris Healthcare. She then was a consultant and data scientist at IBM who focused on healthcare analytics. There, she also led IBM\u2019s Employee Charitable Contribution Campaign<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ibm.com/blogs/citizen-ibm/2013/05/finding-time-to-participate-in-ibms-culture-of-service/|title=Finding Time to Participate in IBM\u2019s Culture of Service - Citizen IBM Blog|date=2013-05-14|work=Citizen IBM Blog|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref> and founded the After Hours Gaming League for [[StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty|StarCraft II]] with a team that made it to the league gaming finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sc2casts.com/cast8260-IBM-vs-Epic-Best-of-7-After-Hours-Gaming-League-Finals|title=IBM vs Epic - After Hours Gaming League Finals - Apr 25, 2012 - Starcraft 2 VOD  - All Starcraft 2 video casted matches / VODs in one place !|website=sc2casts.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Day9TV|title=AHGL IBM vs Epic Award Ceremony - Season 2 Grand Finals - Starcraft 2|date=2012-04-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K5PkihrQKaE|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> At Google, she held roles in product management, technical program management, and data science on [[Google Health]], Google People Operations, and [[Google Search]]. She founded Google\u2019s first Business Intelligence Summit, called SELECT*.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/wogrammer/posts/1757404707825304:0|title=wogrammer|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n[[File:2015 Kathy Pham United States Digital Service at White House.jpg|left|thumb|Pham at the [[United States Digital Service]] ]]\nPham left Google in 2014 to join and build the [[United States Digital Service]], where she led and contributed to public services across the Veterans Affairs, Department of Defense, Precision Medicine Initiative, and Cancer Moonshot, spanning engineering, product management, and people operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/barack-obama-google-tech-talent-government-websites-118064|title=Obama's tech troops|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> Pham was a guest speaker to the White House State of Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (SoSTEM), following the [[State of the Union]] address in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2015/01/22/microbes-apps-and-backflips-space-3rd-annual-white-house-state-stem-event-kids|title=Microbes, Apps, and Backflips-in-Space at 3rd Annual White House \"State of STEM\" Event for Kids|date=2015-01-22|work=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> \n\nPham was a 2017-2019 Fellow, and now Affiliate, at Harvard University\u2019s [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman Klein Center]] for Internet and Society, where her research spans technology, policy, healthcare, artificial intelligence, and the social responsibility and ethics of the tech industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/events/2018/luncheon/04/ethicaltech|title=Honoring All Expertise: Social Responsibility and Ethics in Tech|website=cyber.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/newsroom/2017_2018_community|title=Berkman Klein Center Announces 2017-2018 Community {{!}} Berkman Klein Center|website=cyber.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> As a member of the [https://bkmla.org/ 2018 MIT Media Lab and Berkman Klein Center Assembly], Pham's work addressed the ethics and governance of [[Artificial intelligence|Artificial Intelligence]] with a focus on community involvement and community voices,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bkmla.org/2018/2018people.html|title=Assembly|website=bkmla.org|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> and she co-founded ai-in-the-loop. Pham teaches Product Management and Society at the Harvard Kennedy School of government.\n\nPham is active with outreach and activism,<ref>{{Citation|last=AnitaB_org|title=Megan Smith - Importance of Diverse Ideas in Gov't GHC15|date=2015-11-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ILzUpCA_ozE&t=7m11s|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/momscancode/posts/1532408010162632:0|title=Moms Can: CODE|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/wogrammer/kathy-pham-235ae4d57e9b|title=Kathy Pham|last=wogrammer|date=2016-03-01|website=wogrammer|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/beth-cone-kramer/inspiring-girls-in-the-te_b_8023776.html|title=Inspiring Girls in the Tech Space: 100 Girls To Code|last=Kramer|first=Beth Cone|date=2015-08-26|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> and has been notable for bringing her infant daughter along for a keynote address prompting the hashtag #LittleKeynoteSpeaker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:6257571453756145664|title=#LittleKeynoteSpeaker|last=|first=|date=|website=www.linkedin.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She works closely with immigrant communities to help navigate government services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jennifer-pahlka/government-for-the-people_b_9038610.html|title=Government for the People|last=Pahlka|first=Jennifer|date=2016-01-21|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> Pham has served as an advisory board member of the [[Anita Borg Institute]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/netflix-hosts-abisilicon-valley-event-lilit-yenokyan/|title=Netflix hosts ABI.Silicon Valley event|date=2017-05-31|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref> and the Make the Breast Pump Not Suck Initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.katekrontiris.com/home/2017/11/9/look-within-reach-across-anchor-down-reflections-on-white-privilege-changemaking-and-moral-courage-in-the-age-of-magic-and-loss|title=\"Look Within, Reach Across, Anchor Down:\" Reflections on white privilege, changemaking, and moral courage in the \"age of magic and loss\"|work=Kate Krontiris|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.makethebreastpumpnotsuck.com/team/|title=Leadership Team & Advisory Board|website=\"Make the Breast Pump Not Suck!\" Hackathon|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref>\n\nPham is the founder and executive director of the Cancer Sidekick Foundation and the founder of the Boston Chapter of Women in Product.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@stephaneill/building-women-in-product-dc-7a9d35020ec0|title=Building Women in Product DC|last=Neill|first=Stephanie J.|date=2018-04-06|website=Stephanie J. Neill|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref> She coined the term Cancer Patient Sidekick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ignitetalks.io/videos/life-as-a-patient-sidekick|title=IgniteTalks.io {{!}} Life as a Patient Sidekick by Kathy Pham|last=Lead|first=Stephen|website=www.ignitetalks.io|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n[[File:Children Interview Kathy Pham Megan Smith at SOSTEM 2015.jpg|thumb|Kathy Pham and [[Megan Smith]] interviewed at [https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2015/01/22/microbes-apps-and-backflips-space-3rd-annual-white-house-state-stem-event-kids State of STEM] at the White House]]\n\n* Commencement Speaker, Harvard University, [[Harvard Extension School|Extension School]] (2019)\n*One of the youngest members to be inducted in the [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] Greek Hall of Fame. (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://greek.gatech.edu/content/greek-hall-fame|title=Greek Hall of Fame {{!}} Greek Affairs|website=greek.gatech.edu|language=af|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n*First Lady Michelle Obama\u2019s Guest to the 2015 [[State of the Union]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2015/01/19/meet-kathy-pham-guest-first-lady-state-union|title=Meet Kathy Pham, a Guest of the First Lady at the State of the Union|date=2015-01-19|website=whitehouse.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n*[[Nguoi Viet Daily News|Nguoi Viet\u2019]]<nowiki/>s 40 under 40<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nguoi-viet.com/newarticle/Nguoi-Viet-tieu-bieu-duoi-40-tuoi-Kathy-Pham-3652/|title=Ng\u01b0\u1eddi Vi\u1ec7t ti\u00eau bi\u1ec3u d\u01b0\u1edbi 40 tu\u1ed5i: Kathy Ph\u1ea1m|date=2015-03-18|work=Nguoi Viet Online|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*First Place, representing the United States in the international [[Imagine Cup]] \u201cOlympics for Technology\u201d competition with over 300,000 competitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gatech.edu/2009/07/08/ga-tech-team-receives-top-honors-2009-imagine-cup|title=Ga. Tech Team Receives Top Honors  in 2009 Imagine Cup|website=www.news.gatech.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/microsoftuseducation/2009/07/10/us-students-win-in-egypt-at-imagine-cup-2009-worldwide-finals/|title=US Students Win in Egypt at Imagine Cup 2009 Worldwide Finals|work=Education Insights|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jamie|url=http://www.dailycitizen.news/news/local_news/team-curious-featuring-former-dalton-resident-prevails-in-microsoft-competition/article_f019a26b-8d8c-527a-9b25-6e2d98710fc4.html|title=\"Team Curious\" featuring former Dalton resident prevails in Microsoft competition|work=The Daily Citizen|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref>\n*Georgia Tech [[Georgia Institute of Technology College of Computing|College of Computing]]\u2019s Most Outstanding Junior<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cc.gatech.edu/content/annual-awards-and-honors-past-recipients|title=Annual Awards and Honors - Past Recipients {{!}} College of Computing|website=www.cc.gatech.edu|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n*Finalist for the Anita Borg Memorial Scholarship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2008/04/congratulations-to-our-us-and-canadian.html|title=Congratulations to our U.S. and Canadian Anita Borg Scholars|website=Official Google Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n*[[Salutatorian]] of Windsor Forest High School graduating class<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtoc.com/story/27896047/savannah-woman-selected-to-attend-the-state-of-the-union-address|title=Savannah woman selected to attend the State of the Union address|website=https://www.wtoc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.kathypham.com/ KathyPham.com]\n* [https://www.usds.gov/people/kathy-pham Profile at USDS.gov]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pham, Kathy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Google employees]]\n[[Category:Berkman Fellows]]\n[[Category:Executive Office of the President of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kathy Pham\n| image              = Kathy-pham.jpg\n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], [[Sup\u00e9lec]], [[MIT Media Lab]], [[Harvard University]]\n| employer           = [[United States Digital Service]], [[Google]], [[IBM]], Georgia Tech Research Institute\n| boards             = [[Anita Borg Institute for Women and Technology]], Make the Breast Pump Not Suck\n}}\n'''Kathy Pham''' is a Vietnamese American [[computer scientist]] and [[Product manager|product leader]]. She served as a founding product and engineering member of the [[United States Digital Service]] (USDS) in the [[Executive Office of the President of the United States]] at [[White House|The White House]], and has held roles in leadership, engineering, product management, and data science at [[Google]], [[IBM]], the [[Georgia Tech Research Institute]], and Harris Healthcare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/barack-obama-google-tech-talent-government-websites-118064|title=Obama's tech troops|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/01/21/uncle-sam-needs-more-geeks/|title=Uncle Sam Needs More Geeks \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/the-u-s-digital-service/why-i-joined-the-u-s-digital-service-24c6682afce2|title=Why I Joined the U.S. Digital Service|last=Service|first=The U. S. Digital|date=2015-01-28|website=The U.S. Digital Service|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref>\n\nPham is a Fellow and Adjunct Lecturer on product management at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]], a Fellow at the [[Mozilla Foundation]], and Affiliate at the Harvard [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman Klein Center]] where she co-founded and leads the Ethical Tech Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2018/08/21/mozilla-announces-25-new-fellows-in-openness-science-and-tech-policy/|title=Mozilla Announces 26 New Fellows in Openness, Science, and Tech Policy \u2013 The Mozilla Blog|website=The Mozilla Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/digitalhks/meet-senior-fellow-kathy-pham-aa1f741bdfa1|title=Meet Senior Fellow Kathy Pham|last=Weber|first=Eva|date=2018-08-21|website=digital HKS|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/events/2018/luncheon/04/ethicaltech|title=Honoring All Expertise: Social Responsibility and Ethics in Tech|date=2018-07-06|website=Berkman Klein Center|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref> Pham co-leads the Responsible Computer Science Challenge at Mozilla alongside [[Omidyar Network]], [[Craig Newmark]] Philanthropies, and Schmidt Futures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2018/10/10/announcing-a-competition-for-ethics-in-computer-science-with-up-to-3-5-million-in-prizes/|title=Announcing a Competition for Ethics in Computer Science, with up to $3.5 Million in Prizes \u2013 The Mozilla Blog|website=The Mozilla Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-03}}</ref>\n== Early life and education ==\nPham\u2019s parents were [[Vietnamese boat people]], who spent several years in refugee camps before immigrating to the United States. Her brother, [[United States Marine Corps]] Captain David Pham, was presented the [[Purple Heart]] medal during combat operations in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gov.gatech.edu/hg/item/365761|title=Government & Community Relations {{!}} Georgia Institute of Technology {{!}} Atlanta, GA|website=www.gov.gatech.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://phimublog.com/2015/08/07/vibrant-voice-kathy-pham/|title=Vibrant Voice \u2013 Kathy Pham|date=2015-08-07|work=A Vibrant View|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPham attended [[Windsor Forest High School]] in [[Savannah, Georgia]] where she was a member of the volleyball team and graduated as [[Salutatorian]] of her graduating class.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wtoc.com/story/27896047/savannah-woman-selected-to-attend-the-state-of-the-union-address|title=Savannah woman selected to attend the State of the Union Address|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPham earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Computer science|Computer Science]] from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]. She also holds a [[Master of Science]] in Computer Science from both the Georgia Institute of Technology and [[Sup\u00e9lec|Supelec]], specializing in cryptography and human computer interaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gatech.edu/2015/01/20/georgia-tech-grad-among-white-house-guests-state-union|title=Georgia Tech grad among White House guests for State of the Union|website=www.news.gatech.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> While in university, Pham was the chair of Georgia Tech's Women in Computing,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cc.gatech.edu/compiler/archive/compiler-November08.html|title=Compiler - November 2008|website=www.cc.gatech.edu|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> director of technology at Phi Mu Fraternity, researcher in the Bio-Medical Informatics and Bio-Imaging Lab,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openwetware.org/wiki/Summer_2006_Workshop|title=Summer 2006 Workshop - OpenWetWare|website=openwetware.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> and founded the southeast chapter of [[Unite For Sight|United for Sight]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://coe.gatech.edu/news/entrepreneurial-upstarts|title=Entrepreneurial Upstarts|last=km78|date=2015-06-24|work=College of Engineering|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nPham began her career as a software engineer building flights simulation and healthcare interoperability software at the Georgia Tech Research Institute and Harris Healthcare. She then was a consultant and data scientist at IBM who focused on healthcare analytics. There, she also led IBM\u2019s Employee Charitable Contribution Campaign<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ibm.com/blogs/citizen-ibm/2013/05/finding-time-to-participate-in-ibms-culture-of-service/|title=Finding Time to Participate in IBM\u2019s Culture of Service - Citizen IBM Blog|date=2013-05-14|work=Citizen IBM Blog|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref> and founded the After Hours Gaming League for [[StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty|StarCraft II]] with a team that made it to the league gaming finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sc2casts.com/cast8260-IBM-vs-Epic-Best-of-7-After-Hours-Gaming-League-Finals|title=IBM vs Epic - After Hours Gaming League Finals - Apr 25, 2012 - Starcraft 2 VOD  - All Starcraft 2 video casted matches / VODs in one place !|website=sc2casts.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Day9TV|title=AHGL IBM vs Epic Award Ceremony - Season 2 Grand Finals - Starcraft 2|date=2012-04-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K5PkihrQKaE|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> At Google, she held roles in product management, technical program management, and data science on [[Google Health]], Google People Operations, and [[Google Search]]. She founded Google\u2019s first Business Intelligence Summit, called SELECT*.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/wogrammer/posts/1757404707825304:0|title=wogrammer|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n[[File:2015 Kathy Pham United States Digital Service at White House.jpg|left|thumb|Pham at the [[United States Digital Service]] ]]\nPham left Google in 2014 to join and build the [[United States Digital Service]], where she led and contributed to public services across the Veterans Affairs, Department of Defense, Precision Medicine Initiative, and Cancer Moonshot, spanning engineering, product management, and people operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/barack-obama-google-tech-talent-government-websites-118064|title=Obama's tech troops|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> Pham was a guest speaker to the White House State of Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (SoSTEM), following the [[State of the Union]] address in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2015/01/22/microbes-apps-and-backflips-space-3rd-annual-white-house-state-stem-event-kids|title=Microbes, Apps, and Backflips-in-Space at 3rd Annual White House \"State of STEM\" Event for Kids|date=2015-01-22|work=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> \n\nPham is a fellow at Harvard University\u2019s [[Berkman Klein Center for Internet & Society|Berkman Klein Center]] for Internet and Society, where her research spans technology, policy, healthcare, artificial intelligence, and the social responsibility and ethics of the tech industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/events/2018/luncheon/04/ethicaltech|title=Honoring All Expertise: Social Responsibility and Ethics in Tech|website=cyber.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyber.harvard.edu/newsroom/2017_2018_community|title=Berkman Klein Center Announces 2017-2018 Community {{!}} Berkman Klein Center|website=cyber.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> As a member of the [https://bkmla.org/ 2018 MIT Media Lab and Berkman Klein Center Assembly], Pham's work addressed the ethics and governance of [[Artificial intelligence|Artificial Intelligence]] with a focus on community involvement and community voices,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bkmla.org/2018/2018people.html|title=Assembly|website=bkmla.org|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> and she co-founded ai-in-the-loop. Pham teaches Product Management and Society at the Harvard Kennedy School of government.\n\nPham is active with outreach and activism,<ref>{{Citation|last=AnitaB_org|title=Megan Smith - Importance of Diverse Ideas in Gov't GHC15|date=2015-11-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ILzUpCA_ozE&t=7m11s|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/momscancode/posts/1532408010162632:0|title=Moms Can: CODE|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/wogrammer/kathy-pham-235ae4d57e9b|title=Kathy Pham|last=wogrammer|date=2016-03-01|website=wogrammer|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/beth-cone-kramer/inspiring-girls-in-the-te_b_8023776.html|title=Inspiring Girls in the Tech Space: 100 Girls To Code|last=Kramer|first=Beth Cone|date=2015-08-26|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> and has been notable for bringing her infant daughter along for a keynote address prompting the hashtag #LittleKeynoteSpeaker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:6257571453756145664|title=#LittleKeynoteSpeaker|last=|first=|date=|website=www.linkedin.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She works closely with immigrant communities to help navigate government services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jennifer-pahlka/government-for-the-people_b_9038610.html|title=Government for the People|last=Pahlka|first=Jennifer|date=2016-01-21|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> Pham has served as an advisory board member of the [[Anita Borg Institute]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/netflix-hosts-abisilicon-valley-event-lilit-yenokyan/|title=Netflix hosts ABI.Silicon Valley event|date=2017-05-31|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref> and the Make the Breast Pump Not Suck Initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.katekrontiris.com/home/2017/11/9/look-within-reach-across-anchor-down-reflections-on-white-privilege-changemaking-and-moral-courage-in-the-age-of-magic-and-loss|title=\"Look Within, Reach Across, Anchor Down:\" Reflections on white privilege, changemaking, and moral courage in the \"age of magic and loss\"|work=Kate Krontiris|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.makethebreastpumpnotsuck.com/team/|title=Leadership Team & Advisory Board|website=\"Make the Breast Pump Not Suck!\" Hackathon|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref>\n\nPham is the founder and executive director of the Cancer Sidekick Foundation and the founder of the Boston Chapter of Women in Product.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@stephaneill/building-women-in-product-dc-7a9d35020ec0|title=Building Women in Product DC|last=Neill|first=Stephanie J.|date=2018-04-06|website=Stephanie J. Neill|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref> She coined the term Cancer Patient Sidekick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ignitetalks.io/videos/life-as-a-patient-sidekick|title=IgniteTalks.io {{!}} Life as a Patient Sidekick by Kathy Pham|last=Lead|first=Stephen|website=www.ignitetalks.io|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n[[File:Children Interview Kathy Pham Megan Smith at SOSTEM 2015.jpg|thumb|Kathy Pham and [[Megan Smith]] interviewed at [https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2015/01/22/microbes-apps-and-backflips-space-3rd-annual-white-house-state-stem-event-kids State of STEM] at the White House]]\n\n* [[Salutatorian]] of Windsor Forest High School graduating class<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtoc.com/story/27896047/savannah-woman-selected-to-attend-the-state-of-the-union-address|title=Savannah woman selected to attend the State of the Union address|website=https://www.wtoc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n* Finalist for the Anita Borg Memorial Scholarship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2008/04/congratulations-to-our-us-and-canadian.html|title=Congratulations to our U.S. and Canadian Anita Borg Scholars|website=Official Google Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n* Georgia Tech [[Georgia Institute of Technology College of Computing|College of Computing]]\u2019s Most Outstanding Junior<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cc.gatech.edu/content/annual-awards-and-honors-past-recipients|title=Annual Awards and Honors - Past Recipients {{!}} College of Computing|website=www.cc.gatech.edu|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n* First Lady Michelle Obama\u2019s Guest to the 2015 [[State of the Union]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2015/01/19/meet-kathy-pham-guest-first-lady-state-union|title=Meet Kathy Pham, a Guest of the First Lady at the State of the Union|date=2015-01-19|website=whitehouse.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n* One of the youngest members to ever be inducted in the [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] Greek Hall of Fame. (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://greek.gatech.edu/content/greek-hall-fame|title=Greek Hall of Fame {{!}} Greek Affairs|website=greek.gatech.edu|language=af|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n* [[Nguoi Viet Daily News|Nguoi Viet\u2019]]<nowiki/>s 40 under 40<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nguoi-viet.com/newarticle/Nguoi-Viet-tieu-bieu-duoi-40-tuoi-Kathy-Pham-3652/|title=Ng\u01b0\u1eddi Vi\u1ec7t ti\u00eau bi\u1ec3u d\u01b0\u1edbi 40 tu\u1ed5i: Kathy Ph\u1ea1m|date=2015-03-18|work=Nguoi Viet Online|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* Placed 1st representing the United States in the international [[Imagine Cup]] \u201cOlympics for Technology\u201d competition with over 300,000 competitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.gatech.edu/2009/07/08/ga-tech-team-receives-top-honors-2009-imagine-cup|title=Ga. Tech Team Receives Top Honors  in 2009 Imagine Cup|website=www.news.gatech.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/microsoftuseducation/2009/07/10/us-students-win-in-egypt-at-imagine-cup-2009-worldwide-finals/|title=US Students Win in Egypt at Imagine Cup 2009 Worldwide Finals|work=Education Insights|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailycitizen.news/news/local_news/team-curious-featuring-former-dalton-resident-prevails-in-microsoft-competition/article_f019a26b-8d8c-527a-9b25-6e2d98710fc4.html|title=\"Team Curious\" featuring former Dalton resident prevails in Microsoft competition|last=Jones|first=Jamie|work=The Daily Citizen|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.kathypham.com/ KathyPham.com]\n* [https://www.usds.gov/people/kathy-pham Profile at USDS.gov]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pham, Kathy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Google employees]]\n[[Category:Berkman Fellows]]\n[[Category:Executive Office of the President of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Asiwrite", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edits and fixed chronology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathy_Pham"}
