{"title_page": "McKean, Pennsylvania", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|McKean County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = McKean, Pennsylvania\n| settlement_type        = [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|Borough]]\n| image_skyline          = \n| image_alt              = \n| image_caption          = \n| image_flag             = \n| flag_alt               = \n| image_seal             = \n| seal_alt               = \n| image_shield           = \n| shield_alt             = \n| etymology              = \n| nickname               = \n| motto                  = \n| image_map              = Erie County Pennsylvania incorporated and unincorporated areas McKean highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                = 260px\n| map_caption            = Location in [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie County]] and the U.S. state of [[Pennsylvania]].\n| coordinates            = {{coord|41|59|56|N|80|8|44|W|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint          = \n| coordinates_footnotes  = \n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = United States\n| subdivision_type1      = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| subdivision_type2      = County\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie]]\n| established_title      = \n| established_date       = \n| established_title1     = \n| established_date1      = \n| founder                = \n| seat_type              = \n| seat                   = \n| leader_party           = \n| leader_title           = Mayor\n| leader_name            = Curtis G. Hendricks \n| unit_pref              = Imperial\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_42.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Mar 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2         = 1.51\n| area_land_km2          = 1.48\n| area_water_km2         = 0.03\n| area_urban_sq_mi       = \n| area_rural_sq_mi       = \n| area_metro_sq_mi       = \n| area_water_percent     = \n| area_note              = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = <ref name=\"MTopozone\">{{cite web |title=McKean P O and Station Topo Map, Erie County PA (Edinboro North Area) |url=https://www.topozone.com/pennsylvania/erie-pa/locale/mckean-p-o-and-station/ |website=TopoZone |publisher=Locality, LLC |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_ft            = 1022\n| elevation_point         = Borough benchmark\n| elevation_max_footnotes = <ref name=\"MTopozone\"/>\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| elevation_max_ft        = 1,200\n| elevation_max_point     = southeast corner of borough\n| elevation_max_rank      =\n| elevation_min_footnotes = <ref name=\"MTopozone\"/>\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_min_ft        = 985\n| elevation_min_point     = [[Elk Creek (Lake Erie)|Elk Creek]]\n| elevation_min_rank      =\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_total       = 388\n| population_as_of       = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_km2 = 253.19\n| population_demonym     = \n| population_note        = \n| timezone1              = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset1            = -4\n| timezone1_DST          = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST        = -5\n| postal_code_type       = ZIP code\n| postal_code            = 16426\n| area_code_type         = \n| area_code              = [[Area code 814|814]]\n| blank_name_sec1        = \n| blank_info_sec1        = \n| website                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 373\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 42-46216\n|area_total_sq_mi = 0.58\n|area_land_sq_mi = 0.57\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.01\n|population_density_sq_mi = 655.59\n}}\n\n'''McKean''' is a [[borough (Pennsylvania)|borough]] in [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie County]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States. The population was 388 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4246216| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): McKean borough, Pennsylvania| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American Factfinder| accessdate=March 15, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213061002/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4246216| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> It is part of the [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]] [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. McKean was known as \"Middleboro\" until it officially changed its name in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TourErie.com |title=McKean Borough |url=http://www.visiteriepa.com/communities/mckean_borough.shtml |accessdate=2007-07-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306200435/http://visiteriepa.com/communities/mckean_borough.shtml |archivedate=2007-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nMcKean is located in central Erie County at {{coord|41|59|56|N|80|8|44|W|type:city}} (41.998941, -80.145475).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is surrounded by [[McKean Township, Erie County, Pennsylvania|McKean Township]]. [[Pennsylvania Route 99]] passes through the borough, leading north {{convert|5|mi|0}} to [[U.S. Route 19]] in the outskirts of Erie and south {{convert|8|mi|0}} to [[Edinboro, Pennsylvania|Edinboro]]. [[Interstate 79]] passes {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} west of McKean, with access from Exit 174. I-79 leads north {{convert|12|mi}} to downtown Erie and south {{convert|27|mi}} to the [[Meadville, Pennsylvania|Meadville]] area.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], McKean borough has a total area of {{convert|1.5|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|0.03|sqkm|order=flip|2}}, or 1.82%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/> The borough is located along [[Elk Creek (Lake Erie)|Elk Creek]], which flows west to [[Lake Erie]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|align=left\n|1870= 126\n|1880= 210\n|1890= 195\n|1900= 207\n|1910= 207\n|1920= 239\n|1930= 291\n|1940= 320\n|1950= 379\n|1960= 442\n|1970= 462\n|1980= 465\n|1990= 418\n|2000= 389\n|2010= 388\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=373\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources:<ref name=\"USDecennialCensus\">{{cite web|title=Census of Population and Housing|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref><ref name=CensusPopEst>{{cite web|title=Incorporated Places and Minor Civil Divisions Datasets: Subcounty Resident Population Estimates: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|work=Population Estimates|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HQu4Spqa?url=http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|archivedate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 389 people, 150 households, and 100 families residing in the borough. The [[population density]] was 673.6 people per square mile (259.0/km\u00b2). There were 161 housing units at an average density of 278.8 per square mile (107.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the borough was 99.49% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.26% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], and 0.26% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.51% of the population.\n\nThere were 150 households, out of which 38.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.3% were non-families. 26.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.57 and the average family size was 3.17.\n\nIn the borough the population was spread out, with 28.0% under the age of 18, 10.3% from 18 to 24, 25.7% from 25 to 44, 23.7% from 45 to 64, and 12.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females there were 95.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 90.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the borough was [[US Dollar|$]]39,063, and the median income for a family was $46,250. Males had a median income of $31,875 versus $24,844 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the borough was $16,403. About 6.9% of families and 5.4% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 8.8% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Erie County, Pennsylvania}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1795]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Erie County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|McKean County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = McKean, Pennsylvania\n| settlement_type        = [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|Borough]]\n| image_skyline          = \n| image_alt              = \n| image_caption          = \n| image_flag             = \n| flag_alt               = \n| image_seal             = \n| seal_alt               = \n| image_shield           = \n| shield_alt             = \n| etymology              = \n| nickname               = \n| motto                  = \n| image_map              = Erie County Pennsylvania incorporated and unincorporated areas McKean highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                = 260px\n| map_caption            = Location in [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie County]] and the U.S. state of [[Pennsylvania]].\n| coordinates            = {{coord|41|59|56|N|80|8|44|W|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint          = \n| coordinates_footnotes  = \n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = United States\n| subdivision_type1      = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| subdivision_type2      = County\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie]]\n| established_title      = \n| established_date       = \n| established_title1     = \n| established_date1      = \n| founder                = \n| seat_type              = \n| seat                   = \n| leader_party           = \n| leader_title           = Mayor\n| leader_name            = Curtis G. Hendricks \n| unit_pref              = Imperial\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_42.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Mar 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2         = 1.51\n| area_land_km2          = 1.48\n| area_water_km2         = 0.03\n| area_urban_sq_mi       = \n| area_rural_sq_mi       = \n| area_metro_sq_mi       = \n| area_water_percent     = \n| area_note              = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = <ref name=\"MTopozone\">{{cite web |title=McKean P O and Station Topo Map, Erie County PA (Edinboro North Area) |url=https://www.topozone.com/pennsylvania/erie-pa/locale/mckean-p-o-and-station/ |website=TopoZone |publisher=Locality, LLC |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_ft            = 1022\n| elevation_point         = Borough benchmark\n| elevation_max_footnotes = <ref name=\"MTopozone\"/>\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| elevation_max_ft        = 1,200\n| elevation_max_point     = southeast corner of borough\n| elevation_max_rank      =\n| elevation_min_footnotes = <ref name=\"MTopozone\"/>\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_min_ft        = 985\n| elevation_min_point     = [[Elk Creek (Lake Erie)|Elk Creek]]\n| elevation_min_rank      =\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_total       = 388\n| population_as_of       = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_km2 = 253.19\n| population_demonym     = \n| population_note        = \n| timezone1              = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset1            = -4\n| timezone1_DST          = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST        = -5\n| postal_code_type       = ZIP code\n| postal_code            = 16426\n| area_code_type         = \n| area_code              = [[Area code 814|814]]\n| blank_name_sec1        = \n| blank_info_sec1        = \n| website                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 373\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 42-46216\n|area_total_sq_mi = 0.58\n|area_land_sq_mi = 0.57\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.01\n|population_density_sq_mi = 655.59\n}}\n\n'''McKean''' is a [[borough (Pennsylvania)|borough]] in [[Erie County, Pennsylvania|Erie County]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States. The population was 388 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4246216| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): McKean borough, Pennsylvania| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American Factfinder| accessdate=March 15, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213061002/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4246216| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> It is part of the [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]] [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. McKean was known as \"Middleboro\" until it officially changed its name in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TourErie.com |title=McKean Borough |url=http://www.visiteriepa.com/communities/mckean_borough.shtml |accessdate=2007-07-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306200435/http://visiteriepa.com/communities/mckean_borough.shtml |archivedate=2007-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nMcKean is located in central Erie County at {{coord|41|59|56|N|80|8|44|W|type:city}} (41.998941, -80.145475).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> It is surrounded by [[McKean Township, Erie County, Pennsylvania|McKean Township]]. [[Pennsylvania Route 99]] passes through the borough, leading north {{convert|5|mi|0}} to [[U.S. Route 19]] in the outskirts of Erie and south {{convert|8|mi|0}} to [[Edinboro, Pennsylvania|Edinboro]]. [[Interstate 79]] passes {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} west of McKean, with access from Exit 174. I-79 leads north {{convert|12|mi}} to downtown Erie and south {{convert|27|mi}} to the [[Meadville, Pennsylvania|Meadville]] area.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], McKean borough has a total area of {{convert|1.5|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|0.03|sqkm|order=flip|2}}, or 1.82%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/> The borough is located along [[Elk Creek (Lake Erie)|Elk Creek]], which flows west to [[Lake Erie]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|align=left\n|1870= 126\n|1880= 210\n|1890= 195\n|1900= 207\n|1910= 207\n|1920= 239\n|1930= 291\n|1940= 320\n|1950= 379\n|1960= 442\n|1970= 462\n|1980= 465\n|1990= 418\n|2000= 389\n|2010= 388\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=373\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources:<ref name=\"USDecennialCensus\">{{cite web|title=Census of Population and Housing|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref><ref name=CensusPopEst>{{cite web|title=Incorporated Places and Minor Civil Divisions Datasets: Subcounty Resident Population Estimates: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|work=Population Estimates|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HQu4Spqa?url=http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|archivedate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 389 people, 150 households, and 100 families residing in the borough. The [[population density]] was 673.6 people per square mile (259.0/km\u00b2). There were 161 housing units at an average density of 278.8 per square mile (107.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the borough was 99.49% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.26% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], and 0.26% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.51% of the population.\n\nThere were 150 households, out of which 38.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.3% were non-families. 26.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.57 and the average family size was 3.17.\n\nIn the borough the population was spread out, with 28.0% under the age of 18, 10.3% from 18 to 24, 25.7% from 25 to 44, 23.7% from 45 to 64, and 12.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females there were 95.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 90.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the borough was [[US Dollar|$]]39,063, and the median income for a family was $46,250. Males had a median income of $31,875 versus $24,844 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the borough was $16,403. About 6.9% of families and 5.4% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 8.8% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Erie County, Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1795]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Erie County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McKean,_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Jeezy", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Jeezy\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Young Jeezy July 2005 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Jenkins in 2005\n| alt = A black man with a blue bandana and a chain, lightly smiling at an off-screen entity\n| birth_name = Jay Wayne Jenkins\n| alias = {{flatlist|\n* Lil' J\n* Young Jeezy\n* The Snowman\n}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1977|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Columbia, South Carolina]],<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |last=Kellman|first=Andy|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p640485/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title= Young Jeezy: Biography|accessdate=January 16, 2009 |year=2008 |publisher=allmusic }}</ref> U.S.\n| origin = <!-- STOP CHANGING THIS TO MACON WITHOUT A SOURCE -->[[Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Southern hip hop]]\n* [[Trap music|trap]]\n* [[gangsta rap]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jeezy discography|Rapper]]\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* [[#Filmography|actor]]\n}}\n| years_active = 1997&ndash;present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[CTE World]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist| <!-- Exercise constraint and add only the NOTABLE acts associated with Jeezy; see [[Template:Infobox musical artist#Associated acts]] for criteria --> \n* [[Boyz n da Hood]]\n* [[United Streets Dopeboyz of America|USDA]]\n* [[2 Chainz]]\n* [[Boosie Badazz]]\n* [[DJ Drama]]\n* [[Freddie Gibbs]]\n* [[Lil Wayne]]\n* [[Ludacris]]\n* [[Shawty Redd]]\n* [[Yo Gotti]]\n* [[YG (rapper)|YG]]\n* [[Akon]]\n* [[T.I.]]\n* [[Drumma Boy]]\n* [[Lil Reese]]\n* [[Fabolous]]\n* [[Plies (rapper)|Plies]]\n* [[Cash Out]]\n* [[Webbie]]\n* [[YC (rapper)|YC]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|http://jeezyofficial.com}}\n}}\n'''Jay Wayne Jenkins''' (born September 28, 1977), known professionally as '''Jeezy''' (formerly '''Young Jeezy'''), is an American rapper, singer, songwriter, and actor. Signed to [[Def Jam Recordings]] since 2004, his major label debut ''[[Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101]]'' was released the following year and debuted at #2 on the ''Billboard'' 200, selling 172,000 copies in its first week and was later certified [[Platinum certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). Jeezy is credited, along with fellow Atlanta-based rappers [[T.I.]] and [[Gucci Mane]], for helping to pioneer and popularize [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap music]] with a mainstream audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/aug/13/trap-kings-how-hip-hop-sub-genre-dominated-decade|title=Trap kings: how the hip-hop sub-genre dominated the decade|last=Lee|first=Christina|date=August 13, 2015|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/09/28/happy-birthday-young-jeezy/|title=Happy Birthday, Young Jeezy!|date=September 28, 2011|publisher=Rapfix.mtv.com|accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jeezy-officially-drops-young-from-his-name-news.7117.html|title=Jeezy Officially Drops \"Young\" From His Name|publisher=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/09/young-jeezy-halts-interview-announce-new-name-change/|title=Young Jeezy Halts Interview To Announce New Name Change|publisher=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJeezy began his music career in 2001 as '''Lil J''' with the release of ''[[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)]]''. In total, Jeezy has released ten studio albums, as well as numerous successful singles, including the top ten hit \"[[Soul Survivor (Young Jeezy song)|Soul Survivor]]\", featuring [[Akon]], as well as the top 40 hits \"[[I Luv It (Young Jeezy song)|I Luv It]]\", \"[[Go Getta]]\" featuring [[R. Kelly]], and \"[[Put On]]\" featuring [[Kanye West]]. Along with his own singles, Jeezy has also been featured on numerous [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] hit singles, including \"[[Say I]]\" by [[Christina Milian]], \"[[I'm So Paid]]\" by Akon, \"[[Hard (Rihanna song)|Hard]]\" by [[Rihanna]] and \"[[Love in This Club]]\" by [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], the latter of which reached number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], in 2008.\n\nOutside of his solo career, Jeezy is also the ''[[de facto]]'' leader of the [[southern hip hop]] group [[U.S.D.A (band)|United Streets Dopeboyz of America]] (U.S.D.A), and a former member of the [[Bad Boy Records]]' rap group [[Boyz n da Hood]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career beginnings (1977&ndash;2004)===\nJay Wayne Jenkins was born on September 28, 1977 in [[Columbia, South Carolina]]. When he was a toddler, Jenkins relocated to [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] where he lived with different family members, as a result of his parents separating.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /><ref name=\"HIF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/yhif/young_jeezy/|title=Young Jeezy|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=June 1, 2005|work=You Hear It First|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=April 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Mouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/y/young_jeezy/young_jeezy_inw_050801/|title=Young Jeezy: Putting His Mouth Where His Money Is|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=August 1, 2005|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=April 1, 2010}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' magazine, he described his childhood as \"empty\". At a point in time he lived in [[Hawkinsville, Georgia]] at 600 N Lumpkin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgia.arrests.org/Arrests/Jay_Jenkins_5978244/|title=Jay Jenkins Mugshot {{!}} 10/12/01 Georgia Arrest|website=georgia.arrests.org|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> He had lived in [[Macon, Georgia]] at an older age where he befriended many [[Crips|Crip]] gang members and even affiliated himself with the [[Crips]] and started his affiliation with Kinky B who helped his career along with many others.\n\nIn 1994, Jeezy spent nine months in YCA (Youth Challenge Academy), a [[recruit training|boot camp]] in [[Fort Stewart]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], for narcotics possession.<ref name=\"XXL 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/magazine/2005/10/im-a-king/|title=I'm a King|last=Thompson|first=Bonsu|date=October 2005|work=XXL|accessdate=January 13, 2011}}</ref>  Four years later, in 1998, Jeezy launched the label imprint [[CTE World]], then known as Corporate Thugz Entertainment.\n\nIn 2001, under the name Lil J, Young Jeezy released his first independent album, ''[[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)]]'',.<ref name=\"TUI\">{{cite web|url = https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005M96X/|accessdate = November 29, 2006|title=Thuggin Under the Influence |publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> The album included features from artists Freddy J., Kinky B, Fidank, and [[Lil Jon]], who also produced some of the songs. In 2003, Jeezy independently released ''[[Come Shop wit Me]]'', a two-CD set featuring new tracks along with some songs previously released on [[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)|''T.U.I'']]''.'' In 2004, Jeezy signed with [[Bad Boy Records]] and joined the group [[Boyz n da Hood]], whose [[Boyz n da Hood (album)|self-titled album]] was released in June 2005 and peaked at #5 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart.\n\nIn May 2004, [[Jazze Pha]]'s manager, Henry 'Noonie' Lee, showed Jeezy's demo to his friend [[Shakir Stewart]], then Vice President Artist and Repertoire (VP A&R) at Def Jam.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_ShakirStewart.html|title=Interview With Shakir Stewart|date=November 14, 2005|publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|accessdate=June 22, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111223118/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_ShakirStewart.html|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Stewart \"fell in love with it [the demo] the first time [he] heard it\" and took it to [[L.A. Reid]].<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" /> Reid recognized Jeezy's talent and gave Stewart the green light to sign him.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" />  However,  due to Jeezy's rising popularity, other [[record label]]s began pursuing him simultaneously to sign with them, most notably, [[Warner Music Group|Warner]] and [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]. Ultimately, Jeezy decided he wanted to be in business with Stewart and Reid and signed with [[Def Jam Records]] as a result.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" />\n\n===''Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101'' (2005)===\nJeezy released his major label debut, ''[[Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101]]'', on July 26, 2005. The album debuted at #2 on the Billboard 200, selling 172,000 copies in its first week and was later certified Platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"sale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/magazine_features/2006/05/bmf_mo_money_mo_problems/|title=Black Mafia Family \u2013 Mo' Money, Mo' Problems|author=Ethan Brown|date=May 4, 2006|website=Vibe.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061129044400/http://www.vibe.com/news/magazine_features/2006/05/bmf_mo_money_mo_problems/|archivedate=November 29, 2006|url-status=dead|accessdate=November 29, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The debut single off his debut album, \"And Then What\" featured [[Mannie Fresh]] and reached #67 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The second single off the album, \"[[Soul Survivor (Young Jeezy song)|Soul Survivor]]\" featuring [[Akon]], reached #4 on the Billboard Hot 100 and would become Jeezy's highest-charting single of his career. The third single, \"My Hood\", reached #77 on the Billboard Hot 100. In an interview with [[HitQuarters]], A&R Shakir Stewart said that Jeezy had recorded over 60 songs for the album.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" />\n\nIn interviews and on several records, Jeezy has affirmed his resistance to [[commercialism]] in his music.<ref name=\"commercial\">{{cite web|url = http://ezsonglyrics.com/lyrics/young-jeezy/my-hood.html|title = My Hood lyrics|website = Ezsonglyrics/com|accessdate = November 29, 2006|author = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061122184002/http://ezsonglyrics.com/lyrics/young-jeezy/my-hood.html|archive-date = November 22, 2006|url-status = dead}}</ref> According to Jeezy, maintaining his [[Credibility|street credibility]], is of the utmost concern to him as an artist.<ref name=\"XXL 2005\" /> In 2005, Jeezy was featured in several popular hip hop songs including [[Gucci Mane]]'s \"Icy\"<ref name=\"popularicy\">{{cite web|url =http://atlanta.about.com/od/celebrityprofiles/p/guccimane.htm|title =Popular single \"Icy\"|website =Atlanta.about.com|accessdate =November 29, 2006|author =|url-status=dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070125231017/http://atlanta.about.com/od/celebrityprofiles/p/guccimane.htm|archivedate =January 25, 2007|df =mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Boyz n da Hood|Boyz n da Hood's]] \"[[Dem Boyz (Boyz n da Hood song)|Dem Boyz]]\". Although, he would later leave the group after having successfully established himself as a solo artist.\n\n===''The Inspiration'' and U.S.D.A. (2006\u201307)===\n[[File:Young Jeezy (cropped).jpg|thumb|Young Jeezy in 2006]]\nIn 2006, Jeezy was featured in [[Christina Milian]]'s single \"[[Say I]]\". Later that year, on December 12, he released his second major label album, ''[[The Inspiration]]''. It topped the Billboard 200 with first-week sales of 352,000 copies and would go on to be certified Platinum by the RIAA. The album's first single \"[[I Luv It (Young Jeezy song)|I Luv It]]\" peaked at #14 on the Billboard Hot 100 and the second single, \"[[Go Getta]]\" featuring [[R. Kelly]], peaked at #18.\n\nJeezy also extended himself into gaming, portraying himself in the 3D hip-hop fighting game ''[[Def Jam: Icon]],'' released in March 2007. Also in 2007, Jeezy's group [[U.S.D.A (band)|U.S.D.A]] (alongside Blood Raw and [[Slick Pulla]]) released their debut album, ''[[Cold Summer (U.S.D.A. album)|Cold Summer]]''. The album debuted at number 4 on the ''Billboard'' 200, selling 95,000 copies in its first week.\n\nOn December 17, 2007 Jeezy and [[CTE World|CTE]] started their week-long toy drive and charity event series called the Toyz N Da Hood Drive. The series presented 1,000 toys for 1,000 kids at various locations in [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]] and [[Atlanta]]. The CTE Christmas Kickoff portion of the event ran from 10 pm to 5 am at Club Miami. The toy giveaway took place in the Unionville neighborhood of [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]] and at the Old Fourth Ward Community in [[Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hhworlds.com/f11/12-14-07-young-jeezy-hosts-toyz-n-da-hood-10052.html |title='&#39;HHWorlds.com'&#39; \u2013 Young Jeezy Hosts 'Toyz n da Hood' (December 14, 2007) |publisher=Hhworlds.com |date=May 8, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306041653/http://www.hhworlds.com/f11/12-14-07-young-jeezy-hosts-toyz-n-da-hood-10052.html |archivedate=March 6, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===''The Recession'' (2008)===\nOn September 2, 2008 Jeezy released [[The Recession (album)|''The Recession'']], his third [[Album|studio album]] and, what would be, his second consecutive number one album. It topped the Billboard 200, selling 260,000 copies in its first week and was later [[Music recording certification|certified gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. The album's lead single, \"[[Put On]]\", featured [[Kanye West]]<nowiki/>and reached #12 on the Billboard Hot 100. [[The Recession (album)|T''he Recession'']] also earned Jeezy a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for Best Rap performance by a duo. Other singles off the album included \"[[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\", \"[[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\", \"[[My President]]\" featuring [[Nas]], and \"[[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\" featuring [[Shawty Redd]].  Separately, Jeezy made appearances on [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher's]]  \"[[Love in This Club]]\" and [[Akon|Akon's]] \"[[I'm So Paid]]\"  which also with [[Lil Wayne]]. \"[[Love in This Club]]\" peaked at #1 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Later, Jeezy performed on [[Ciara]]'s single \"[[Never Ever (Ciara song)|Never Ever]]\", from her album ''[[Fantasy Ride]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/12/19/ciara-better-than-ever-on-new-single/|title=Ciara's New Single Confirmed|publisher=Rap-Up.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, Jeezy was at the center of a controversy over his choice for president. While he had previously endorsed Barack Obama, during an interview with [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']], Jeezy spoke about meeting and supporting John McCain. The statement caused a stir, and Jeezy quickly clarified his stance via a viral video. In the four-minute explanation, Jeezy made it clear, Obama was his main choice. \"I represent the Democratic party. ... I've never been nor do I ever plan to be a John McCain supporter\", the rapper said. \"I support Barack Obama.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Starbury|first=Allen|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/article/news/2008/07/5016/|title=Young Jeezy Clarifies McCain Comments, Pledges Support For Obama|work=BallerStatus.com|date=July 2, 2008}}</ref> Jeezy and [[Jay-Z]] performed in a concert to celebrate the inauguration of President [[Barack Obama]] on January 18, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=St. Pierre|first=Jay|url=http://www.lsureveille.com/opinion/get_sillay_young_jeezy_enforces_country_s_racial_segregation-1.1485034|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223010844/http://www.lsureveille.com/opinion/get_sillay_young_jeezy_enforces_country_s_racial_segregation-1.1485034|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 23, 2009|title=Get Sillay: Young Jeezy enforces country's racial segregation|work=The Daily Reveille|date=February 19, 2009}}</ref> On ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'', commentator [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] criticized their performance as a \"rant that offended people\", but Jeezy responded: \"I got white friends. It's nothing like that. I'm a taxpayer, I got a right to voice my opinion at any point in time. I don't think he really understands my struggle.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1603361/20090122/jeezy_young.jhtml|title=Young Jeezy Defends 'My President' Against Bill O'Reilly|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=March 15, 2009|publisher=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Kanye West Explains 'Jockin' Jay-Z' Sample, Drops Exclusive Freestyle, More In Mixtape Monday|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1605130/20090213/west_kanye.jhtml|work=Mixtape Monday|publisher=MTV News|date=February 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===''TM:103 Hustlerz Ambition'' and ''Its Tha World'' (2010\u201312)===\nIt was announced on November 2009 that Jeezy started working on ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615584/20090708/story.jhtml|title=Young Jeezy Is Working On Thug Motivation 103 'Right Now'|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=July 9, 2009|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=July 27, 2009}}</ref> In March 2010, it was reported that Young Jeezy dropped \"Young\" from his stage name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islanddefjam.com/artist/news_single.aspx?nid=6457&artistID=7320|title=Young Jeezy Changes His Name.|publisher=Islanddefjam.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> Later, Young Jeezy denied the name change and claimed it was just a rumor:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/young-jeezy/041310-jeezy-says-his-name-is-still-young-jeezy.html|title=Jeezy denies name change says he still Young Jeezy - Young Jeezy|publisher=Rap Basement|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> However, on the cover for his single \"[[Lose My Mind (Young Jeezy song)|Lose My Mind]]\", his name is printed as \"Jeezy\". \"[[Lose My Mind (Young Jeezy song)|Lose My Mind]]\" peaked at #35 on the Billboard Hot 100.\n\nOn March 4, 2010, Jeezy released \"Illin\", featuring [[Clipse]], more specifically, [[Pusha T]]. On the track [[Pusha T]] raps, \"No amount of record sales could derail this ...Stuffing dead prezzies in the wall like that Yale bitch...\" The line was controversial as many felt the line was in bad taste. Here Jeezy is alluding to Yale student Annie Le, who was [[Murder of Annie Le|murdered]] in 2009. Many felt Young Jeezy was making light of Le's tragic death.<ref>Gendreau, Leanne. (September 20, 2010) [http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local-beat/Rap-Lyric-Makes-Light-of-Annie-Le-Murder--103338064.html Rap Lyric Makes Light of Annie Le Murder]. NBC New York. Retrieved on December 27, 2010.</ref>\n\nNearly two years after first announcing work on ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'', on May 17, 2011, Jeezy released the first single off ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'', \"Ballin\", which features [[Lil Wayne]] and peaked at #57 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Two months later, on July 22, 2011, the second intended single off the album was released, a track called \"Shake Life,\" although it was later scrapped. On July 26, 2011, Jeezy announced a September 20, 2011 release date for ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/07/25/young-jeezy-announces-tm103-release-date/ |title=Young Jeezy Announces 'TM103' Release Date |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=July 25, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> However the album was pushed back yet again, this time to December 20, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16909/title.rap-release-dates-young-jeezy-mac-miller-bow-wow-dj-drama |title=Rap Release Dates: Young Jeezy, Mac Miller, Bow Wow, DJ Drama &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=September 20, 2011 |accessdate=October 31, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026055001/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16909/title.rap-release-dates-young-jeezy-mac-miller-bow-wow-dj-drama |archive-date=October 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On September 29, 2011, Jeezy released the third single off ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'', named \"F.A.M.E.\" (Fake Ass Motherfuckers Envy), featuring [[T.I.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashionably-early.com/2011/09/29/young-jeezy-%e2%80%93-f-a-m-e-fake-ass-muthafckas-envy-f-t-i/|title=Young Jeezy \u2013 F.A.M.E. (Fake Ass Muthaf*ckas Envy) f. T.I|date=September 29, 2011|publisher=Fashionably-early.com|accessdate=October 31, 2011}}</ref> The song was [[T.I.]]'s first appearance on a song since his release from prison. On December 20, 2011, ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'' was finally released. The album debuted at #3 on the Billboard 200, selling 233,000 copies in its first week, becoming certified Gold by the RIAA. \"I Do\" featuring [[Andr\u00e9 3000]] and [[Jay-Z]] was the album's fourth single; it peaked at #61 on the Billboard Hot 100. \"Leave You Alone\" featuring [[Ne-Yo]] was the album's fifth single and reached #51 on the Billboard Hot 100. In 2012, Young Jeezy's \"I Do\" received a [[Grammy]] nomination for Best Rap Performance.\n \nIn October 2012, Jeezy released a new single called \"Get Right\" on [[ITunes]] and sent it to radio. Shortly after the single's release, Jeezy confirmed he had plans to release a new mixtape by the end of 2012 as well as a new album in 2013. On December 12, 2012, Jeezy released ''[[It's Tha World]]'', the aforementioned mixtape, hosted by [[DJ Drama]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://theversed.com/2012/10/11/young-jeezy-get-right-new-music/|title=Young Jeezy \u2013 Get Right [New Music] - The Versed|publisher=Theversed.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212185209/http://theversed.com/2012/10/11/young-jeezy-get-right-new-music/|archivedate=February 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/young-jeezy-reveals-its-tha-world-mixtape-details|title=Young Jeezy Reveals 'Its Tha World' Mixtape Details - Vibe|date=December 1, 2012|publisher=Vibe.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> The mixtape features [[2 Chainz]], [[Trey Songz]], [[Lil Boosie]], [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]] and [[E-40]]. Production came from [[Jahlil Beats]], The Renegades, [[DJ Mustard]], [[Warren G]], [[Mike WiLL Made It]], [[Cardo]] and Black Metaphor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/Young-Jeezy-Its-Tha-World-mixtape.425097.html|title=Young Jeezy - Its Tha World Hosted by Dj Drama // Free Mixtape @ DatPiff.com|work=DatPiff|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Boss Yo Life Up Gang, Seen It All: The Autobiography'' and ''Church in These Streets'' (2013\u20132015)===\n[[File:Young Jeezy 2014.jpg|thumb|left|Young Jeezy Performs \"Go Getta\" and \"Soul Survivor\" in 2014]]\nOn August 13, 2013, Young Jeezy released a compilation mixtape titled ''[[Boss Yo Life Up Gang]]'' with [[CTE World]] artists, Doughboyz Cashout and [[YG (rapper)|YG]] . The mixtape has two singles, \"[[My Nigga (song)|My Nigga]]\" by YG and \"Mob Life\" by Doughboyz Cashout, both of which Young Jeezy was featured on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2013/08/14/download-young-jeezy-yg-doughboyz-cashouts-boss-your-life-up-gang-mixtape/ |title=Download Young Jeezy, YG & DoughBoyz Cashout's 'Boss Your Life Up Gang' Mixtape |publisher=TheSource |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref> On September 17, 2013, Jeezy premiered the first single \"In My Head\" produced by [[Childish Major]], from his CTE collaboration mixtape \"Its Tha World 2\". The following day he announced plans to release his next album, saying it will more deeply detail his street origins. He revealed that [[Future (rapper)|Future]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Ludacris]], and [[Don Cannon]] would be involved in the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/09/jeezy-announces-new-album/ |title=Jeezy Announces New Album - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=September 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/jeezy-new-album-future-ludacris-usher |title=Jeezy New Album Future, Ludacris, and Usher |publisher=Complex |date=September 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2014, Jeezy released the first single \"Me Ok\" from his upcoming fifth studio album ''[[Seen It All: The Autobiography]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/me-ok-single/id883464362|title=iTunes Store|publisher=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> On July 1, 2014, he released the second single, \"[[Seen It All (Young Jeezy song)|Seen It All]]\", featuring [[Jay-Z]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/seen-it-all-feat.-jay-z-single/id893739140 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |accessdate=September 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701161908/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/seen-it-all-feat.-jay-z-single/id893739140 |archivedate=July 1, 2014 }}</ref> On August 31, 2015, Jeezy announced that he would release a new project entitled ''[[Church in These Streets]]''. Four singles were released and the project as a whole came on November 13, 2015. It debuted at #4 on the [[Billboard 200]].\n\n===''Trap or Die 3'', ''Pressure'', ''TM104: The Legend of the Snowman'' and retirement (2016\u2013present)===\nOn October 28, 2016, Jeezy released his new album ''[[Trap or Die 3]]'', which became available for pre-order on iTunes earlier that month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jeezy-reveals-tracklist-for-trap-or-die-3-news.24739.html? |title=Jeezy's Trap or Die 3 is available for pre-order |last=Goddard |first=Kevin |website=Hotnewhiphop |date=October 14, 2016 |access-date=October 14, 2016}}</ref> It debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, becoming Jeezy's third album to top the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7565778/jeezy-third-no-1-billboard-200-chart|title=Jeezy Earns His Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Trap or Die 3'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2017, Jeezy released his eighth studio album ''[[Pressure (Jeezy album)|Pressure]]'' (originally titled Snow Season).\n\nOn July 25, 2019, Jeezy announced that his final album ''[[TM104: The Legend of the Snowman]]'' was released on August 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesource.com/2019/07/29/jeezy-announces-release-date-for-thug-motivation-104/|title=Jeezy Announces Release Date for 'Thug Motivation 104'|last=Grant|first=Shawn|date=2019-07-29|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter [[Hurricane Katrina]], Jeezy opened his house to victims, offering those who had been displaced from their homes a place to stay.  In October 2005, the mother of his 9-year-old son used his act as the basis to petition for [[child support]]. Early in the year, she had claimed that she had little income, no assets, and did not even have a house. Young Jeezy has a sister named Katrina Wright.<ref name=\"openhouse\">{{cite news|url =http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=1409|title = Jeezy helps hurricane victims|accessdate = November 29, 2006|author = |date= October 21, 2005| work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\nIn September 2019, [[Jeannie Mai]] revealed that she has been dating the rapper.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a29070486/jeannie-mai-opens-up-jeezy/ |title = The Real's Jeannie Mai Opens up About Dating Rapper Jeezy: \"I Found My Equal\"|date = September 16, 2019}}</ref> The couple became engaged on March 27, 2020.<ref> {{Cite web | url= https://people.com/tv/jeannie-mai-engaged-jeezy-relationship-photos/|title=Jeannie Mai and Jeezy's Sweetest Moments, from Going Public to Getting Engaged|work=People|publisher=Meredith Corporation|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nOn March 11, 2005, Jeezy was arrested after an alleged shooting involving some of his friends in Miami Beach, Florida.<ref>{{cite news|title= Young Jeezy arrested after Florida shootout|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/11808183|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205031405/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/11808183|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 5, 2010|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=June 27, 2010|date=March 16, 2006}}</ref> He was charged with two counts of carrying a concealed firearm without a permit; however, prosecutors dropped his charges two months later over lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title= Young Jeezy weapons charges dropped|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/12818427|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208021641/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/12818427|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 8, 2010|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=June 27, 2010|date=May 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the early hours of September 29, 2007, Jeezy destroyed his [[Bugatti Veyron]] when it was hit by a taxi crossing Peachtree Street, outside of Justin's, [[Sean Combs]]'s club in [[Atlanta]]. The ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' reported his claim that the incident had given him \"a new appreciation for life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sohh.com/ya_heard/2007/10/4040_club_stabb.html|title=40/40 Club Stabbing|publisher=Blogs.sohh.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804021130/http://blogs.sohh.com/ya_heard/2007/10/4040_club_stabb.html|archivedate=August 4, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Atlanta on June 18, 2008, Young Jeezy was arrested for [[DUI]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1589553/20080618/jeezy_young.jhtml|title=Young Jeezy Arrested In Atlanta|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=February 3, 2009|publisher=MTV News}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2013, Brian Smith filed a copyright infringement complaint seeking an injunction, damages, and attorney fees against Jay W. Jenkins d/b/a Young Jeezy Music and others in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]], concerning the work \"Jizzle\"  which was released in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watkins|first=Kirk W.|title=Composer Accuses Famed Atlanta Rapper Young Jeezy of Copyright Infringement in Misappropriating Lyrics to Song Provided to Rapper in 2009|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/composer-accuses-famed-atlanta-rapper-young-jeezy-copyright-infringement-misappropri|accessdate=May 18, 2013|newspaper=The [[National Law Review]]|date=May 13, 2013|author2=Womble Carlyle Sandridge & Rice, PLLC}}</ref>\n\nOn August 27, 2013 [[Leroy Hutson]] aka Lee Hutson, Sr., former lead singer of 1970s R&B group [[The Impressions]], filed a complaint against Young Jeezy and others alleging that Young Jeezy's song \"Time\" inappropriately incorporated the instrumental portion of  \"Getting it On\", which was registered with the [[United States Copyright Office]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Heard|first=Preston H.|title=Singer-Songwriter Lee Hutson Sues Rapper Young Jeezy Over Alleged Use of \"Getting It On\" Sample|journal=The [[National Law Review]]|date=September 6, 2013|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/singer-songwriter-lee-hutson-sues-rapper-young-jeezy-over-alleged-use-getting-it-sam|accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2014, Jeezy was arrested for battery, false imprisonment, and terrorist threats, after an alleged fight with his son in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26926/title.jeezy-arrested-on-battery-false-imprisonment-terroristic-threats-charges- |title=Jeezy Arrested On Battery, False Imprisonment & Terroristic Threats Charges |publisher=HipHop DX |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2014, Jeezy was arrested before performing at the [[Irvine, California]] stop on the Under The Influence Tour in connection with the deadly shooting two days prior in the backstage area,  on another stop of the tour in Mountain View, California. When the police raided Jeezy's tour bus, they found an [[AK-47]] military-style assault rifle and guns on several members of his entourage. In total six people, including Jeezy were arrested, because \"no one admitted to owning the assault rifle.\" His bail was set at one million dollars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/08/jeezy-gets-arrested-sunday-utiom-performance/|title=Jeezy Gets Arrested For Gun Possession, Possible Suspect In Wiz Khalifa Concert Shooting|work=XXL|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/08/jeezy-ak-47-cops-tour-bus/|title=Jeezy 47 Cops Tour Bus|publisher=Xxlmag.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> On August 26, Jeezy, as well as the five other men he was arrested with, entered not guilty pleas to possession of an illegal assault rifle. Two days later, Jeezy and his associates bonded out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.30370/title.jeezy-pleads-not-guilty-for-possession-of-ak-47-assault-rifle-posts-bail|title=Jeezy AK-47 Assault Rifle Investigation Proves Firearm Does Not Belong To Rapper - Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales - HipHop DX|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> Officers were reportedly told repeatedly that the registered owner of the AK-47 was the tour security chief, who was hospitalized at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/09/ak-47-jeezy-security-chief/|title=Jeezy Security Chief|publisher=Xxlmag.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Jeezy discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Come Shop wit Me]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Inspiration]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Recession]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[TM:103 Hustlerz Ambition]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Seen It All: The Autobiography]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Church in These Streets]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Trap or Die 3]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Pressure (Jeezy album)|Pressure]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[TM104: The Legend of the Snowman]]'' (2019)\n\n==Filmography==\n*2009: ''[[Janky Promoters]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuperstein |first=Slava |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.7285/title.jeezy-talks-movie-with-ice-cube-remix-with-jay-z |title=Jeezy Talks Movie With Ice Cube, Remix With Jay-Z |publisher=Hiphopdx.com |date=July 10, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n;[[American Music Awards]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[American Music Awards of 2007|2007]]\n| Young Jeezy\n| [[American Music Award for Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Artist|Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Male Artist]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|- \n| ''[[The Inspiration]]''\n| [[American Music Award for Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Album|Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Album]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n;[[BET Awards]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| [[BET Awards 2008|2008]]\n| \"[[I'm So Hood]] (Remix)\"\n| [[BET Award for Best Collaboration|Best Collaboration]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[BET Awards 2009|2009]]\n| Young Jeezy\n| [[BET Award for Best Hip-Hop Artists|Best Male Hip-Hop Artist]]\n| {{Nom}}<ref>[http://www.bet.com/Specials/BETAwards08/betawards-nominees/BestCollaboration.htm]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627210205/http://www.bet.com/Specials/BETAwards08/betawards-nominees/BestCollaboration.htm |date=June 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[BET Awards 2010|2010]]\n| \"[[Hard (Rihanna song)|Hard]]\" <small>(with [[Rihanna]])</small>\n| [[BET Award for Viewer's Choice|Viewer's Choice]]\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n* Note: \"I'm So Hood (Remix)\" with DJ Khaled, Ludacris, Busta Rhymes, Big Boi, Lil Wayne, Fat Joe, Birdman, & Rick Ross\n\n;[[BET Hip Hop Awards]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2006\n| ''Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101''\n| Hip-Hop CD of the Year\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"BET Hip Hop Awards 2006\">{{cite web|url=http://rap.about.com/od/awards/a/BETHipHopAwards.htm|title=2006 BET Hip-Hop Awards|last=Adaso|first=Henry|publisher=About.com|accessdate=April 10, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| Young Jeezy\n| Hip-Hop MVP of the Year\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"BET Hip Hop Awards 2006\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2008\n|rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[I'm So Hood]] (Remix)\"\n| Best Hip-Hop Video\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Hip-Hop Collaboration\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"[[Put On]]\" <small>(featuring Kanye West)</small>\n| People's Champ Award\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n* Note: \"I'm So Hood (Remix)\" with DJ Khaled, Ludacris, Busta Rhymes, Big Boi, Lil Wayne, Fat Joe, Birdman, & Rick Ross\n\n;[[Grammy Award]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| [[51st Annual Grammy Awards|2009]]\n| \"[[Put On]]\" <small>(featuring Kanye West)</small>\n| [[Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[52nd Annual Grammy Awards|2010]]\n| \"[[Amazing (Kanye West song)|Amazing]]\" <small>(with Kanye West)</small>\n| Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards|2011]]\n| \"[[Lose My Mind (Young Jeezy song)|Lose My Mind]]\" <small>(featuring Plies)</small>\n| Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|2013]]\n| \"[[I Do (Young Jeezy song)|I Do]]\" <small>(featuring Jay-Z and Andr\u00e9 3000)</small>\n| [[Best Rap Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n;Ozone Awards{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n{{award table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2007\n| ''The Inspiration''\n| Best Rap Album\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"[[Go Getta]]\" <small>(featuring R. Kelly)</small>\n| Best Rap/R&B Collaboration\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[Grew Up a Screw Up]]\" <small>(with Ludacris)</small>\n| Best Video\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| USDA\n| Best Group\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| Young Jeezy\n| Best Rap Artist\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[Love in This Club]]\" <small>(with Usher)</small>\n| Best Rap/R&B Collaboration\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Young Jeezy}}\n*[http://www.islanddefjam.com/artist/home.aspx?artistID=7320 Official website]\n*{{Discogs artist|341733|Jeezy}}\n\n{{Hip hop}}\n{{Jeezy}}\n{{Def Jam}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Jeezy| ]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:American drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Rappers from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Crips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Jeezy\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Young Jeezy July 2005 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Jenkins in 2005\n| alt = A black man with a blue bandana and a chain, lightly smiling at an off-screen entity\n| birth_name = Jay Wayne Jenkins\n| alias = {{flatlist|\n* Lil' J\n* Young Jeezy\n* The Snowman\n}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Columbia, South Carolina]], U.S.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |last=Kellman|first=Andy|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p640485/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title= Young Jeezy: Biography|accessdate=January 16, 2009 |year=2008 |publisher=allmusic }}</ref>\n| origin = <!-- STOP CHANGING THIS TO MACON WITHOUT A SOURCE -->[[Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Southern hip hop]]\n* [[Trap music|trap]]\n* [[gangsta rap]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jeezy discography|Rapper]]\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* [[#Filmography|actor]]\n}}\n| years_active = 1997&ndash;present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[CTE World]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist| <!-- Exercise constraint and add only the NOTABLE acts associated with Jeezy; see [[Template:Infobox musical artist#Associated acts]] for criteria --> \n* [[Boyz n da Hood]]\n* [[United Streets Dopeboyz of America|USDA]]\n* [[2 Chainz]]\n* [[Boosie Badazz]]\n* [[DJ Drama]]\n* [[Freddie Gibbs]]\n* [[Lil Wayne]]\n* [[Ludacris]]\n* [[Shawty Redd]]\n* [[T.I.]]\n* [[YG (rapper)|YG]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|http://jeezyofficial.com}}\n}}\n'''Jay Wayne Jenkins''' (born September 28, 1977), known professionally as '''Jeezy''' (formerly '''Young Jeezy'''), is an American rapper, singer, songwriter, and actor. Signed to [[Def Jam Recordings]] since 2004, his major label debut ''[[Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101]]'' was released the following year and debuted at #2 on the ''Billboard'' 200, selling 172,000 copies in its first week and was later certified [[Platinum certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). Jeezy is credited, along with fellow Atlanta-based rappers [[T.I.]] and [[Gucci Mane]], for helping to pioneer and popularize [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap music]] with a mainstream audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/aug/13/trap-kings-how-hip-hop-sub-genre-dominated-decade|title=Trap kings: how the hip-hop sub-genre dominated the decade|last=Lee|first=Christina|date=August 13, 2015|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/09/28/happy-birthday-young-jeezy/|title=Happy Birthday, Young Jeezy!|date=September 28, 2011|publisher=Rapfix.mtv.com|accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jeezy-officially-drops-young-from-his-name-news.7117.html|title=Jeezy Officially Drops \"Young\" From His Name|publisher=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/09/young-jeezy-halts-interview-announce-new-name-change/|title=Young Jeezy Halts Interview To Announce New Name Change|publisher=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJeezy began his music career in 2001 as '''Lil J''' with the release of ''[[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)]]''. In total, Jeezy has released ten studio albums, as well as numerous successful singles, including the top ten hit \"[[Soul Survivor (Young Jeezy song)|Soul Survivor]]\", featuring [[Akon]], as well as the top 40 hits \"[[I Luv It (Young Jeezy song)|I Luv It]]\", \"[[Go Getta]]\" featuring [[R. Kelly]], and \"[[Put On]]\" featuring [[Kanye West]]. Along with his own singles, Jeezy has also been featured on numerous [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] hit singles, including \"[[Say I]]\" by [[Christina Milian]], \"[[I'm So Paid]]\" by Akon, \"[[Hard (Rihanna song)|Hard]]\" by [[Rihanna]] and \"[[Love in This Club]]\" by [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], the latter of which reached number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], in 2008.\n\nOutside of his solo career, Jeezy is also the ''[[de facto]]'' leader of the [[southern hip hop]] group [[U.S.D.A (band)|United Streets Dopeboyz of America]] (U.S.D.A), and a former member of the [[Bad Boy Records]]' rap group [[Boyz n da Hood]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career beginnings (1977&ndash;2004)===\nJay Wayne Jenkins was born on September 28, 1977 in [[Columbia, South Carolina]]. When he was a toddler, Jenkins relocated to [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] where he lived with different family members, as a result of his parents separating.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /><ref name=\"HIF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/yhif/young_jeezy/|title=Young Jeezy|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=June 1, 2005|work=You Hear It First|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=April 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Mouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/y/young_jeezy/young_jeezy_inw_050801/|title=Young Jeezy: Putting His Mouth Where His Money Is|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=August 1, 2005|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=April 1, 2010}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' magazine, he described his childhood as \"empty\". At a point in time he lived in [[Hawkinsville, Georgia]] at 600 N Lumpkin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgia.arrests.org/Arrests/Jay_Jenkins_5978244/|title=Jay Jenkins Mugshot {{!}} 10/12/01 Georgia Arrest|website=georgia.arrests.org|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> He had lived in [[Macon, Georgia]] at an older age where he befriended many [[Crips|Crip]] gang members and even affiliated himself with the [[Crips]] and started his affiliation with Kinky B who helped his career along with many others.\n\nIn 1994, Jeezy spent nine months in YCA (Youth Challenge Academy), a [[recruit training|boot camp]] in [[Fort Stewart]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], for narcotics possession.<ref name=\"XXL 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/magazine/2005/10/im-a-king/|title=I'm a King|last=Thompson|first=Bonsu|date=October 2005|work=XXL|accessdate=January 13, 2011}}</ref>  Four years later, in 1998, Jeezy launched the label imprint [[CTE World]], then known as Corporate Thugz Entertainment.\n\nIn 2001, under the name Lil J, Young Jeezy released his first independent album, ''[[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)]]'',.<ref name=\"TUI\">{{cite web|url = https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005M96X/|accessdate = November 29, 2006|title=Thuggin Under the Influence |publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> The album included features from artists Freddy J., Kinky B, Fidank, and [[Lil Jon]], who also produced some of the songs. In 2003, Jeezy independently released ''[[Come Shop wit Me]]'', a two-CD set featuring new tracks along with some songs previously released on [[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)|''T.U.I'']]''.'' In 2004, Jeezy signed with [[Bad Boy Records]] and joined the group [[Boyz n da Hood]], whose [[Boyz n da Hood (album)|self-titled album]] was released in June 2005 and peaked at #5 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart.\n\nIn May 2004, [[Jazze Pha]]'s manager, Henry 'Noonie' Lee, showed Jeezy's demo to his friend [[Shakir Stewart]], then Vice President Artist and Repertoire (VP A&R) at Def Jam.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_ShakirStewart.html|title=Interview With Shakir Stewart|date=November 14, 2005|publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|accessdate=June 22, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111223118/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_ShakirStewart.html|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Stewart \"fell in love with it [the demo] the first time [he] heard it\" and took it to [[L.A. Reid]].<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" /> Reid recognized Jeezy's talent and gave Stewart the green light to sign him.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" />  However,  due to Jeezy's rising popularity, other [[record label]]s began pursuing him simultaneously to sign with them, most notably, [[Warner Music Group|Warner]] and [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]. Ultimately, Jeezy decided he wanted to be in business with Stewart and Reid and signed with [[Def Jam Records]] as a result.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" />\n\n===''Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101'' (2005)===\nJeezy released his major label debut, ''[[Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101]]'', on July 26, 2005. The album debuted at #2 on the Billboard 200, selling 172,000 copies in its first week and was later certified Platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"sale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/magazine_features/2006/05/bmf_mo_money_mo_problems/|title=Black Mafia Family \u2013 Mo' Money, Mo' Problems|author=Ethan Brown|date=May 4, 2006|website=Vibe.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061129044400/http://www.vibe.com/news/magazine_features/2006/05/bmf_mo_money_mo_problems/|archivedate=November 29, 2006|url-status=dead|accessdate=November 29, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The debut single off his debut album, \"And Then What\" featured [[Mannie Fresh]] and reached #67 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The second single off the album, \"[[Soul Survivor (Young Jeezy song)|Soul Survivor]]\" featuring [[Akon]], reached #4 on the Billboard Hot 100 and would become Jeezy's highest-charting single of his career. The third single, \"My Hood\", reached #77 on the Billboard Hot 100. In an interview with [[HitQuarters]], A&R Shakir Stewart said that Jeezy had recorded over 60 songs for the album.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\" />\n\nIn interviews and on several records, Jeezy has affirmed his resistance to [[commercialism]] in his music.<ref name=\"commercial\">{{cite web|url = http://ezsonglyrics.com/lyrics/young-jeezy/my-hood.html|title = My Hood lyrics|website = Ezsonglyrics/com|accessdate = November 29, 2006|author = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061122184002/http://ezsonglyrics.com/lyrics/young-jeezy/my-hood.html|archive-date = November 22, 2006|url-status = dead}}</ref> According to Jeezy, maintaining his [[Credibility|street credibility]], is of the utmost concern to him as an artist.<ref name=\"XXL 2005\" /> In 2005, Jeezy was featured in several popular hip hop songs including [[Gucci Mane]]'s \"Icy\"<ref name=\"popularicy\">{{cite web|url =http://atlanta.about.com/od/celebrityprofiles/p/guccimane.htm|title =Popular single \"Icy\"|website =Atlanta.about.com|accessdate =November 29, 2006|author =|url-status=dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070125231017/http://atlanta.about.com/od/celebrityprofiles/p/guccimane.htm|archivedate =January 25, 2007|df =mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Boyz n da Hood|Boyz n da Hood's]] \"[[Dem Boyz (Boyz n da Hood song)|Dem Boyz]]\". Although, he would later leave the group after having successfully established himself as a solo artist.\n\n===''The Inspiration'' and U.S.D.A. (2006\u201307)===\n[[File:Young Jeezy (cropped).jpg|thumb|Young Jeezy in 2006]]\nIn 2006, Jeezy was featured in [[Christina Milian]]'s single \"[[Say I]]\". Later that year, on December 12, he released his second major label album, ''[[The Inspiration]]''. It topped the Billboard 200 with first-week sales of 352,000 copies and would go on to be certified Platinum by the RIAA. The album's first single \"[[I Luv It (Young Jeezy song)|I Luv It]]\" peaked at #14 on the Billboard Hot 100 and the second single, \"[[Go Getta]]\" featuring [[R. Kelly]], peaked at #18.\n\nJeezy also extended himself into gaming, portraying himself in the 3D hip-hop fighting game ''[[Def Jam: Icon]],'' released in March 2007. Also in 2007, Jeezy's group [[U.S.D.A (band)|U.S.D.A]] (alongside Blood Raw and [[Slick Pulla]]) released their debut album, ''[[Cold Summer (U.S.D.A. album)|Cold Summer]]''. The album debuted at number 4 on the ''Billboard'' 200, selling 95,000 copies in its first week.\n\nOn December 17, 2007 Jeezy and [[CTE World|CTE]] started their week-long toy drive and charity event series called the Toyz N Da Hood Drive. The series presented 1,000 toys for 1,000 kids at various locations in [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]] and [[Atlanta]]. The CTE Christmas Kickoff portion of the event ran from 10 pm to 5 am at Club Miami. The toy giveaway took place in the Unionville neighborhood of [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]] and at the Old Fourth Ward Community in [[Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hhworlds.com/f11/12-14-07-young-jeezy-hosts-toyz-n-da-hood-10052.html |title='&#39;HHWorlds.com'&#39; \u2013 Young Jeezy Hosts 'Toyz n da Hood' (December 14, 2007) |publisher=Hhworlds.com |date=May 8, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306041653/http://www.hhworlds.com/f11/12-14-07-young-jeezy-hosts-toyz-n-da-hood-10052.html |archivedate=March 6, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===''The Recession'' (2008)===\nOn September 2, 2008 Jeezy released [[The Recession (album)|''The Recession'']], his third [[Album|studio album]] and, what would be, his second consecutive number one album. It topped the Billboard 200, selling 260,000 copies in its first week and was later [[Music recording certification|certified gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. The album's lead single, \"[[Put On]]\", featured [[Kanye West]]<nowiki/>and reached #12 on the Billboard Hot 100. [[The Recession (album)|T''he Recession'']] also earned Jeezy a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for Best Rap performance by a duo. Other singles off the album included \"[[Vacation (Young Jeezy song)|Vacation]]\", \"[[Crazy World (Young Jeezy song)|Crazy World]]\", \"[[My President]]\" featuring [[Nas]], and \"[[Who Dat (Young Jeezy song)|Who Dat]]\" featuring [[Shawty Redd]].  Separately, Jeezy made appearances on [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher's]]  \"[[Love in This Club]]\" and [[Akon|Akon's]] \"[[I'm So Paid]]\"  which also with [[Lil Wayne]]. \"[[Love in This Club]]\" peaked at #1 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Later, Jeezy performed on [[Ciara]]'s single \"[[Never Ever (Ciara song)|Never Ever]]\", from her album ''[[Fantasy Ride]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/12/19/ciara-better-than-ever-on-new-single/|title=Ciara's New Single Confirmed|publisher=Rap-Up.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, Jeezy was at the center of a controversy over his choice for president. While he had previously endorsed Barack Obama, during an interview with [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']], Jeezy spoke about meeting and supporting John McCain. The statement caused a stir, and Jeezy quickly clarified his stance via a viral video. In the four-minute explanation, Jeezy made it clear, Obama was his main choice. \"I represent the Democratic party. ... I've never been nor do I ever plan to be a John McCain supporter\", the rapper said. \"I support Barack Obama.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Starbury|first=Allen|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/article/news/2008/07/5016/|title=Young Jeezy Clarifies McCain Comments, Pledges Support For Obama|work=BallerStatus.com|date=July 2, 2008}}</ref> Jeezy and [[Jay-Z]] performed in a concert to celebrate the inauguration of President [[Barack Obama]] on January 18, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=St. Pierre|first=Jay|url=http://www.lsureveille.com/opinion/get_sillay_young_jeezy_enforces_country_s_racial_segregation-1.1485034|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223010844/http://www.lsureveille.com/opinion/get_sillay_young_jeezy_enforces_country_s_racial_segregation-1.1485034|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 23, 2009|title=Get Sillay: Young Jeezy enforces country's racial segregation|work=The Daily Reveille|date=February 19, 2009}}</ref> On ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'', commentator [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] criticized their performance as a \"rant that offended people\", but Jeezy responded: \"I got white friends. It's nothing like that. I'm a taxpayer, I got a right to voice my opinion at any point in time. I don't think he really understands my struggle.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1603361/20090122/jeezy_young.jhtml|title=Young Jeezy Defends 'My President' Against Bill O'Reilly|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=March 15, 2009|publisher=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Kanye West Explains 'Jockin' Jay-Z' Sample, Drops Exclusive Freestyle, More In Mixtape Monday|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1605130/20090213/west_kanye.jhtml|work=Mixtape Monday|publisher=MTV News|date=February 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===''TM:103 Hustlerz Ambition'' and ''Its Tha World'' (2010\u201312)===\nIt was announced on November 2009 that Jeezy started working on ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615584/20090708/story.jhtml|title=Young Jeezy Is Working On Thug Motivation 103 'Right Now'|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=July 9, 2009|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=July 27, 2009}}</ref> In March 2010, it was reported that Young Jeezy dropped \"Young\" from his stage name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islanddefjam.com/artist/news_single.aspx?nid=6457&artistID=7320|title=Young Jeezy Changes His Name.|publisher=Islanddefjam.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> Later, Young Jeezy denied the name change and claimed it was just a rumor:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/young-jeezy/041310-jeezy-says-his-name-is-still-young-jeezy.html|title=Jeezy denies name change says he still Young Jeezy - Young Jeezy|publisher=Rap Basement|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> However, on the cover for his single \"[[Lose My Mind (Young Jeezy song)|Lose My Mind]]\", his name is printed as \"Jeezy\". \"[[Lose My Mind (Young Jeezy song)|Lose My Mind]]\" peaked at #35 on the Billboard Hot 100.\n\nOn March 4, 2010, Jeezy released \"Illin\", featuring [[Clipse]], more specifically, [[Pusha T]]. On the track [[Pusha T]] raps, \"No amount of record sales could derail this ...Stuffing dead prezzies in the wall like that Yale bitch...\" The line was controversial as many felt the line was in bad taste. Here Jeezy is alluding to Yale student Annie Le, who was [[Murder of Annie Le|murdered]] in 2009. Many felt Young Jeezy was making light of Le's tragic death.<ref>Gendreau, Leanne. (September 20, 2010) [http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local-beat/Rap-Lyric-Makes-Light-of-Annie-Le-Murder--103338064.html Rap Lyric Makes Light of Annie Le Murder]. NBC New York. Retrieved on December 27, 2010.</ref>\n\nNearly two years after first announcing work on ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'', on May 17, 2011, Jeezy released the first single off ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'', \"Ballin\", which features [[Lil Wayne]] and peaked at #57 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Two months later, on July 22, 2011, the second intended single off the album was released, a track called \"Shake Life,\" although it was later scrapped. On July 26, 2011, Jeezy announced a September 20, 2011 release date for ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/07/25/young-jeezy-announces-tm103-release-date/ |title=Young Jeezy Announces 'TM103' Release Date |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=July 25, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> However the album was pushed back yet again, this time to December 20, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16909/title.rap-release-dates-young-jeezy-mac-miller-bow-wow-dj-drama |title=Rap Release Dates: Young Jeezy, Mac Miller, Bow Wow, DJ Drama &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=September 20, 2011 |accessdate=October 31, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026055001/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16909/title.rap-release-dates-young-jeezy-mac-miller-bow-wow-dj-drama |archive-date=October 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On September 29, 2011, Jeezy released the third single off ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'', named \"F.A.M.E.\" (Fake Ass Motherfuckers Envy), featuring [[T.I.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashionably-early.com/2011/09/29/young-jeezy-%e2%80%93-f-a-m-e-fake-ass-muthafckas-envy-f-t-i/|title=Young Jeezy \u2013 F.A.M.E. (Fake Ass Muthaf*ckas Envy) f. T.I|date=September 29, 2011|publisher=Fashionably-early.com|accessdate=October 31, 2011}}</ref> The song was [[T.I.]]'s first appearance on a song since his release from prison. On December 20, 2011, ''[[Thug Motivation 103]]'' was finally released. The album debuted at #3 on the Billboard 200, selling 233,000 copies in its first week, becoming certified Gold by the RIAA. \"I Do\" featuring [[Andr\u00e9 3000]] and [[Jay-Z]] was the album's fourth single; it peaked at #61 on the Billboard Hot 100. \"Leave You Alone\" featuring [[Ne-Yo]] was the album's fifth single and reached #51 on the Billboard Hot 100. In 2012, Young Jeezy's \"I Do\" received a [[Grammy]] nomination for Best Rap Performance.\n \nIn October 2012, Jeezy released a new single called \"Get Right\" on [[ITunes]] and sent it to radio. Shortly after the single's release, Jeezy confirmed he had plans to release a new mixtape by the end of 2012 as well as a new album in 2013. On December 12, 2012, Jeezy released ''[[It's Tha World]]'', the aforementioned mixtape, hosted by [[DJ Drama]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://theversed.com/2012/10/11/young-jeezy-get-right-new-music/|title=Young Jeezy \u2013 Get Right [New Music] - The Versed|publisher=Theversed.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212185209/http://theversed.com/2012/10/11/young-jeezy-get-right-new-music/|archivedate=February 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/young-jeezy-reveals-its-tha-world-mixtape-details|title=Young Jeezy Reveals 'Its Tha World' Mixtape Details - Vibe|date=December 1, 2012|publisher=Vibe.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> The mixtape features [[2 Chainz]], [[Trey Songz]], [[Lil Boosie]], [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]] and [[E-40]]. Production came from [[Jahlil Beats]], The Renegades, [[DJ Mustard]], [[Warren G]], [[Mike WiLL Made It]], [[Cardo]] and Black Metaphor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/Young-Jeezy-Its-Tha-World-mixtape.425097.html|title=Young Jeezy - Its Tha World Hosted by Dj Drama // Free Mixtape @ DatPiff.com|work=DatPiff|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Boss Yo Life Up Gang, Seen It All: The Autobiography'' and ''Church in These Streets'' (2013\u20132015)===\n[[File:Young Jeezy 2014.jpg|thumb|left|Young Jeezy Performs \"Go Getta\" and \"Soul Survivor\" in 2014]]\nOn August 13, 2013, Young Jeezy released a compilation mixtape titled ''[[Boss Yo Life Up Gang]]'' with [[CTE World]] artists, Doughboyz Cashout and [[YG (rapper)|YG]] . The mixtape has two singles, \"[[My Nigga (song)|My Nigga]]\" by YG and \"Mob Life\" by Doughboyz Cashout, both of which Young Jeezy was featured on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2013/08/14/download-young-jeezy-yg-doughboyz-cashouts-boss-your-life-up-gang-mixtape/ |title=Download Young Jeezy, YG & DoughBoyz Cashout's 'Boss Your Life Up Gang' Mixtape |publisher=TheSource |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref> On September 17, 2013, Jeezy premiered the first single \"In My Head\" produced by [[Childish Major]], from his CTE collaboration mixtape \"Its Tha World 2\". The following day he announced plans to release his next album, saying it will more deeply detail his street origins. He revealed that [[Future (rapper)|Future]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Ludacris]], and [[Don Cannon]] would be involved in the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/09/jeezy-announces-new-album/ |title=Jeezy Announces New Album - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=September 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/jeezy-new-album-future-ludacris-usher |title=Jeezy New Album Future, Ludacris, and Usher |publisher=Complex |date=September 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2014, Jeezy released the first single \"Me Ok\" from his upcoming fifth studio album ''[[Seen It All: The Autobiography]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/me-ok-single/id883464362|title=iTunes Store|publisher=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> On July 1, 2014, he released the second single, \"[[Seen It All (Young Jeezy song)|Seen It All]]\", featuring [[Jay-Z]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/seen-it-all-feat.-jay-z-single/id893739140 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |accessdate=September 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701161908/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/seen-it-all-feat.-jay-z-single/id893739140 |archivedate=July 1, 2014 }}</ref> On August 31, 2015, Jeezy announced that he would release a new project entitled ''[[Church in These Streets]]''. Four singles were released and the project as a whole came on November 13, 2015. It debuted at #4 on the [[Billboard 200]].\n\n===''Trap or Die 3'', ''Pressure'', ''TM104: The Legend of the Snowman'' and retirement (2016\u2013present)===\nOn October 28, 2016, Jeezy released his new album ''[[Trap or Die 3]]'', which became available for pre-order on iTunes earlier that month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jeezy-reveals-tracklist-for-trap-or-die-3-news.24739.html? |title=Jeezy's Trap or Die 3 is available for pre-order |last=Goddard |first=Kevin |website=Hotnewhiphop |date=October 14, 2016 |access-date=October 14, 2016}}</ref> It debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, becoming Jeezy's third album to top the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7565778/jeezy-third-no-1-billboard-200-chart|title=Jeezy Earns His Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Trap or Die 3'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2017, Jeezy released his eighth studio album ''[[Pressure (Jeezy album)|Pressure]]'' (originally titled Snow Season).\n\nOn July 25, 2019, Jeezy announced that his final album ''[[TM104: The Legend of the Snowman]]'' was released on August 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesource.com/2019/07/29/jeezy-announces-release-date-for-thug-motivation-104/|title=Jeezy Announces Release Date for 'Thug Motivation 104'|last=Grant|first=Shawn|date=2019-07-29|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter [[Hurricane Katrina]], Jeezy opened his house to victims, offering those who had been displaced from their homes a place to stay.  In October 2005, the mother of his 9-year-old son used his act as the basis to petition for [[child support]]. Early in the year, she had claimed that she had little income, no assets, and did not even have a house. Young Jeezy has a sister named Katrina Wright.<ref name=\"openhouse\">{{cite news|url =http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=1409|title = Jeezy helps hurricane victims|accessdate = November 29, 2006|author = |date= October 21, 2005| work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\nIn September 2019, [[Jeannie Mai]] revealed that she has been dating the rapper.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a29070486/jeannie-mai-opens-up-jeezy/ |title = The Real's Jeannie Mai Opens up About Dating Rapper Jeezy: \"I Found My Equal\"|date = September 16, 2019}}</ref> The couple became engaged on March 27, 2020.<ref> {{Cite web | url= https://people.com/tv/jeannie-mai-engaged-jeezy-relationship-photos/|title=Jeannie Mai and Jeezy's Sweetest Moments, from Going Public to Getting Engaged|work=People|publisher=Meredith Corporation|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nOn March 11, 2005, Jeezy was arrested after an alleged shooting involving some of his friends in Miami Beach, Florida.<ref>{{cite news|title= Young Jeezy arrested after Florida shootout|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/11808183|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205031405/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/11808183|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 5, 2010|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=June 27, 2010|date=March 16, 2006}}</ref> He was charged with two counts of carrying a concealed firearm without a permit; however, prosecutors dropped his charges two months later over lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title= Young Jeezy weapons charges dropped|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/12818427|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208021641/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/12818427|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 8, 2010|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=June 27, 2010|date=May 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the early hours of September 29, 2007, Jeezy destroyed his [[Bugatti Veyron]] when it was hit by a taxi crossing Peachtree Street, outside of Justin's, [[Sean Combs]]'s club in [[Atlanta]]. The ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' reported his claim that the incident had given him \"a new appreciation for life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sohh.com/ya_heard/2007/10/4040_club_stabb.html|title=40/40 Club Stabbing|publisher=Blogs.sohh.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804021130/http://blogs.sohh.com/ya_heard/2007/10/4040_club_stabb.html|archivedate=August 4, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Atlanta on June 18, 2008, Young Jeezy was arrested for [[DUI]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1589553/20080618/jeezy_young.jhtml|title=Young Jeezy Arrested In Atlanta|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=February 3, 2009|publisher=MTV News}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2013, Brian Smith filed a copyright infringement complaint seeking an injunction, damages, and attorney fees against Jay W. Jenkins d/b/a Young Jeezy Music and others in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]], concerning the work \"Jizzle\"  which was released in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watkins|first=Kirk W.|title=Composer Accuses Famed Atlanta Rapper Young Jeezy of Copyright Infringement in Misappropriating Lyrics to Song Provided to Rapper in 2009|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/composer-accuses-famed-atlanta-rapper-young-jeezy-copyright-infringement-misappropri|accessdate=May 18, 2013|newspaper=The [[National Law Review]]|date=May 13, 2013|author2=Womble Carlyle Sandridge & Rice, PLLC}}</ref>\n\nOn August 27, 2013 [[Leroy Hutson]] aka Lee Hutson, Sr., former lead singer of 1970s R&B group [[The Impressions]], filed a complaint against Young Jeezy and others alleging that Young Jeezy's song \"Time\" inappropriately incorporated the instrumental portion of  \"Getting it On\", which was registered with the [[United States Copyright Office]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Heard|first=Preston H.|title=Singer-Songwriter Lee Hutson Sues Rapper Young Jeezy Over Alleged Use of \"Getting It On\" Sample|journal=The [[National Law Review]]|date=September 6, 2013|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/singer-songwriter-lee-hutson-sues-rapper-young-jeezy-over-alleged-use-getting-it-sam|accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2014, Jeezy was arrested for battery, false imprisonment, and terrorist threats, after an alleged fight with his son in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26926/title.jeezy-arrested-on-battery-false-imprisonment-terroristic-threats-charges- |title=Jeezy Arrested On Battery, False Imprisonment & Terroristic Threats Charges |publisher=HipHop DX |accessdate=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2014, Jeezy was arrested before performing at the [[Irvine, California]] stop on the Under The Influence Tour in connection with the deadly shooting two days prior in the backstage area,  on another stop of the tour in Mountain View, California. When the police raided Jeezy's tour bus, they found an [[AK-47]] military-style assault rifle and guns on several members of his entourage. In total six people, including Jeezy were arrested, because \"no one admitted to owning the assault rifle.\" His bail was set at one million dollars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/08/jeezy-gets-arrested-sunday-utiom-performance/|title=Jeezy Gets Arrested For Gun Possession, Possible Suspect In Wiz Khalifa Concert Shooting|work=XXL|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/08/jeezy-ak-47-cops-tour-bus/|title=Jeezy 47 Cops Tour Bus|publisher=Xxlmag.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> On August 26, Jeezy, as well as the five other men he was arrested with, entered not guilty pleas to possession of an illegal assault rifle. Two days later, Jeezy and his associates bonded out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.30370/title.jeezy-pleads-not-guilty-for-possession-of-ak-47-assault-rifle-posts-bail|title=Jeezy AK-47 Assault Rifle Investigation Proves Firearm Does Not Belong To Rapper - Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales - HipHop DX|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> Officers were reportedly told repeatedly that the registered owner of the AK-47 was the tour security chief, who was hospitalized at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/09/ak-47-jeezy-security-chief/|title=Jeezy Security Chief|publisher=Xxlmag.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Jeezy discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Thuggin' Under the Influence (T.U.I.)]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Come Shop wit Me]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Inspiration]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Recession]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[TM:103 Hustlerz Ambition]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Seen It All: The Autobiography]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Church in These Streets]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Trap or Die 3]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Pressure (Jeezy album)|Pressure]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[TM104: The Legend of the Snowman]]'' (2019)\n\n==Filmography==\n*2009: ''[[Janky Promoters]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuperstein |first=Slava |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.7285/title.jeezy-talks-movie-with-ice-cube-remix-with-jay-z |title=Jeezy Talks Movie With Ice Cube, Remix With Jay-Z |publisher=Hiphopdx.com |date=July 10, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n;[[American Music Awards]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[American Music Awards of 2007|2007]]\n| Young Jeezy\n| [[American Music Award for Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Artist|Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Male Artist]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|- \n| ''[[The Inspiration]]''\n| [[American Music Award for Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Album|Favorite Rap/Hip-Hop Album]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n;[[BET Awards]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| [[BET Awards 2008|2008]]\n| \"[[I'm So Hood]] (Remix)\"\n| [[BET Award for Best Collaboration|Best Collaboration]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[BET Awards 2009|2009]]\n| Young Jeezy\n| [[BET Award for Best Hip-Hop Artists|Best Male Hip-Hop Artist]]\n| {{Nom}}<ref>[http://www.bet.com/Specials/BETAwards08/betawards-nominees/BestCollaboration.htm]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627210205/http://www.bet.com/Specials/BETAwards08/betawards-nominees/BestCollaboration.htm |date=June 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[BET Awards 2010|2010]]\n| \"[[Hard (Rihanna song)|Hard]]\" <small>(with [[Rihanna]])</small>\n| [[BET Award for Viewer's Choice|Viewer's Choice]]\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n* Note: \"I'm So Hood (Remix)\" with DJ Khaled, Ludacris, Busta Rhymes, Big Boi, Lil Wayne, Fat Joe, Birdman, & Rick Ross\n\n;[[BET Hip Hop Awards]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2006\n| ''Let's Get It: Thug Motivation 101''\n| Hip-Hop CD of the Year\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"BET Hip Hop Awards 2006\">{{cite web|url=http://rap.about.com/od/awards/a/BETHipHopAwards.htm|title=2006 BET Hip-Hop Awards|last=Adaso|first=Henry|publisher=About.com|accessdate=April 10, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| Young Jeezy\n| Hip-Hop MVP of the Year\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"BET Hip Hop Awards 2006\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2008\n|rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[I'm So Hood]] (Remix)\"\n| Best Hip-Hop Video\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Hip-Hop Collaboration\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"[[Put On]]\" <small>(featuring Kanye West)</small>\n| People's Champ Award\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n* Note: \"I'm So Hood (Remix)\" with DJ Khaled, Ludacris, Busta Rhymes, Big Boi, Lil Wayne, Fat Joe, Birdman, & Rick Ross\n\n;[[Grammy Award]]\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| [[51st Annual Grammy Awards|2009]]\n| \"[[Put On]]\" <small>(fea